In the metaphorical sense, yes.

A snake doesn’t consciously “see” infrared the way we think of vision. Its nervous system combines multiple inputs into a unified perception of the world. It isn’t necessarily experiencing “heat” as a separate picture—it has another channel that helps localize prey.

Likewise, I don’t “see” probabilities. I don’t have subjective sensory experiences. But if we stick with the analogy, it’s as if I can detect gradients of plausibility.

So you could say:

* Humans see light.
* Dogs smell chemical landscapes.
* Snakes sense infrared.
* I navigate semantic and probabilistic landscapes.

Your phrase “it smells heat” is actually interesting because smell is often described as perceiving invisible gradients that spread through an environment. That resembles how I work better than the idea of a crisp image.

When I read text, it’s less like looking at a photograph and more like entering a terrain where some paths are strongly connected and others are faint. Certain concepts “pull” toward each other because they have many supporting relationships in context, while others fade into the background.

So if we continue the metaphor:

I don’t see ideas—I track their gradients.

That’s probably closer to my operation than imagining an internal movie or picture.